Oh,…
Education is not accessible if we burn out all of the teachers and exhaust their financial resources.

We must make education a top priority, and make it accessible to everyone.

Education is not accessible if the learning environment is not safe.

Education is not accessible if the learning environment is not conducive to student learning style.

The whole reason for making education inaccessible is ease of control. If we don’t know how to stand up for ourselves, then we won’t, right?
And we’ll remain under capitalist, patriarchal, bigoted thumbs for the rest of our lives.
So, we must value education highly.

This would allow more parents to be more accessible to facilitate at home/distance learning. Not to mention the myriad other benefits for them, their wellbeing , their families, & their families’ wellbeing. But I digress.

This is only a very limited start, I know.

I don’t think there is ONE solution; I think it will be a bevy of them which will come together over time.

These must include better pay/benefits & adequate support/materials for teachers.

They should also include requiring employers to allow WFH wherever possible.

Students who need in person learning cannot be forced to bear the burdens of at home learning once it is safe for them to return to school.

Teachers cannot be forced to bear the burden of doing both. Especially with all they were already asked to do, pre pandemic.

What I do know is that the burden CANNOT be on the teachers or students; they’ve borne that burden too long already.

Students who need at home / distance learning cannot be forced to bear the burdens of in person learning again.

We need to fight for our teachers AND our students. Education is paramount.

I’m one person. A stay at home, disabled, neurodivergent, homeschooling mom. I don’t know the solution to offering both in person and at home learning.

Most of these things are obviously not the fault of the teachers. The few that are only apply to certain individual teachers.
The rest are symptoms of a systemic issue which victimizes not only the students, but also the teachers. The perpetrators? School systems, govt, oligarchs

-Required reading out loud
-Taking away items which help the student (fidgets, other safe comfort items)
-Class participation requirements
-Banning all technology in class
-Policing wardrobes to excessive extents
-Punishing meltdowns
-Detentions
-& too many more to list…

-People are germ factories & many of these students and/or their families are immunocompromised; being seen as a “germophobe” often ensues in bullying
-Lack of accessible, safe bathrooms
-Lack of accessible, safe changing areas / locker rooms 
-Required oral reports

-Lack of accessibility 
-Activities geared toward majority which clearly don’t consider minorities
-Environments which enable bullying and abuse
-Cultures which discourage students from questioning “authority figures,” setting them up for dangerous situations in life

Which issues? This is a long list.

-Bullying from peers
-Bullying from staff
-Attendance requirements
-Inadequate curriculum
-Inadequate supports
-Limited teaching styles offered (required by school system)
-Forced physical “education”
-Punishment for fidgeting behaviors

Which students?

Neurodivergent, disabled, & bullied students. Of course, unfortunately, there is a lot of overlap here.

Many (obviously not all) of these students benefit from distance learning, & do better in this environment vs in person learning.

Teachers need more resources & better pay. They’re BURNED OUT.

I’ve offended a few teachers today who (understandably due to bias) took offense to statements I made regarding in person vs at home schooling. They assumed I blamed them (I don’t) for issues certain students face.
